[[Image:ARM-Cambridge.jpg|thumb|right|The entrance to ARM1, one of the buildings on ARM campus in [[Cambridge]], England ({{coord|52.18177|N|0.17824|E|type:landmark_region:GB}}) ]]
[[Image:Cambridge ARM building panorama.jpg|thumb|right|The ARM I building at Peterhouse Technology Park, Cambridge. The building is a work by architects Barber <U+2013> Casanovas <U+2013> Ruffles .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcr-architects.co.uk/projects/arm.htm|title=Barber Casanovas Ruffles - Chartered Architects: Arm, Peterhouse Technology Park|work=bcr-architects.co.uk|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>]]

'''ARM Holdings plc''' (ARM) is a British [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[semiconductor]] and [[Computer software|software]] design company with its head office in [[Cambridge]], England. Its largest business is designing [[Central processing unit|processors]] (CPU) bearing the [[ARM architecture|ARM]] name, although it also designs [[software development tools]] under the DS-5, RealView and [[Keil (company)|Keil]] brands, [[Platform (computing)|systems and platforms]], [[system-on-a-chip]] (SoC) infrastructure and software.  It is considered to be [[Market dominance|market dominant]] in the field of processors for mobile phones ([[smartphone]]s or otherwise) and [[tablet computer]]s and is arguably the best-known of the '[[Silicon Fen]]' companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://techon.nikkeibp.co.jp/NEA/archive/200204/177680/ |title=ARM CPU Core Dominates Mobile Market <U+2013> Nikkei Electronics Asia <U+2013> Tech-On! |publisher=Techon.nikkeibp.co.jp |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>

Processors based on designs licensed from ARM, or designed by licensees of one of the [[ARM architecture|ARM instruction set architectures]], are used in all classes of computing devices from [[microcontroller]]s in [[embedded system]]s &ndash; including [[Real-time computing|real-time]] safety systems (cars' [[anti-lock braking system|ABS]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arm.com/products/processors/instruction-set-architectures/armv8-r-architecture.php|title=ARMv8-R Architecture|work=arm.com|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> [[Smart TV|smartTVs]] ([[Google TV]]) and all modern [[smartwatch]]es (such as [[Qualcomm Toq]]) &ndash; up to smartphones (such as all [[Apple Inc.|Apple's]] [[iPhone]]s), tablets (such as all Apple's [[iPad]]s), [[laptops]] (some [[Chromebook]] versions), [[Desktop computer|desktops]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/02/09/building-windows-for-the-arm-processor-architecture.aspx|title=MSDN Blogs|publisher=Microsoft|work=msdn.com|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://arm.com/about/newsroom/23761.php ARM and Canonical to Bring Full Ubuntu Desktop Experience to Low-Power, ARM Technology-Based Computing Devices] ARM, 13 November 2008</ref> (first use was in the [[Acorn Archimedes]]), [[Server (computing)|servers]]<ref>[http://www.eweek.com/servers/red-hat-deploys-arm-based-servers-for-fedora-project/ Red Hat Deploys ARM-Based Servers for Fedora Project] Eweek, 15 May 2013</ref> and [[supercomputers]]/[[High-performance computing|HPC]].<ref>[http://insidehpc.com/2013/06/17/ncore-hpc-rolls-out-browndwarf-arm-dsp-supercomputer/ nCore HPC Rolls Out BrownDwarf ARM DSP Supercomputer] Inside HPC, 17 June 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1260737 Nvidia: ARM supercomputer to be more efficient than x86] EE Times, 12 June 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.pcworld.com/article/2039798/smartphone-chips-could-replace-server-processors-in-hpc-researchers-say.html Smartphone chips may power servers, researchers say] PC World, 25 May 2013</ref>

ARM's [[Mali (GPU)|Mali line]] of [[graphics processing unit]]s (GPU) are used in laptops (some Chromebook versions), [[Android (operating system)|Android]] tablets (over 50% market share<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arm.com/products/multimedia/index.php|title=Multimedia - Graphics Processing from ARM|work=arm.com|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>) and smartphones (such as some versions of [[Samsung|Samsung's]] products up to the [[Samsung Galaxy Note 4]] tablet and [[Samsung Galaxy S 5]] smartphone) and smartwatches ([[Samsung Galaxy Gear]]). It is third most popular in mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1319626 |title= ARM Closes in on Imagination in GPU Shipments|first=Peter |last=Clarke|date= 26 September 2013}}</ref>

Systems, including [[iPhone]] smartphones, frequently include many chips, from many different providers, that include one or more licensed ARM cores, in addition to those in the main (ARM-based) processor;<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cpushack.com/tag/qualcomm/ |title=Apple iPhone Update: Whats changed since the iPhone 4 |date=6 September 2012}}</ref> Chips for all common network related technologies: [[Bluetooth]], [[WiFi]] and [[broadband]]<ref>{{cite press |url=http://www.broadcom.com/products/Wireless-LAN/802.11-Wireless-LAN-Solutions/BCM4330 |title=802.11a/b/g/n MAC/Baseband/Radio with Integrated Bluetooth 4.0+HS & FM Transceiver |accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> (and non-network related functions such as with [[Apple M7]]) in smartphones, in addition to corresponding equipments such as [[Bluetooth headset]]s,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcom.com/products/Bluetooth/Bluetooth-RF-Silicon-and-Software-Solutions/BCM2044 |title=Single-Chip Bluetooth<U+00AE> Mono Headset IC |accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> up to newest [[802.11ac]] [[Router (computing)|router]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/5925/broadcom-announces-bcm4708x-and-bcm5301x-socs-for-80211ac-routers |title=ARM: Broadcom Announces BCM4708x and BCM5301x SoCs for 802.11ac routers |first=Brian |last=Klug |date=5 June 2012 |accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref> and provider's cellular [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]].<ref>{{cite press |url=http://investor.marvell.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=120802&p=RssLanding_pf&cat=news&id=1884905 |title=Marvell Expands its Broad 4G LTE Product Portfolio with the ARMADA Mobile PXA1088LTE Pro Platform to Support the Issuing of 4G TD-LTE Licenses in China and Operators |accessdate=21 September 2014}}</ref>

ARM's main CPU competitors include [[Intel]] (Atom), [[Imagination Technologies]] (MIPS) and [[AMD]] (that will also sell 64-bit server processors<ref>{{cite press|url=http://community.amd.com/community/amd-blogs/amd-business/blog/2014/01/28/amd-announces-plans-to-sample-64-bit-arm-opteron-a-seattle-processors |title=AMD announces plans to sample 64-bit ARM Opteron A <U+201C>Seattle<U+201D> processors |publisher=AMD Business |date=28 January 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>), and its GPU competitors include Imagination Technologies (PowerVR), [[Qualcomm]] (Adreno) and increasingly [[Nvidia]] and Intel. Qualcomm and Nvidia combine their GPUs with an ARM licensed CPU while Intel doesn't.

ARM has a primary listing on the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is a constituent of the [[FTSE 100 Index]]. It has a secondary listing on [[NASDAQ]].

==History==

===Name===
The acronym [[ARM architecture|ARM]], first used in 1983, originally stood for "Acorn RISC Machine", the processor from [[Acorn Computers]], its first [[Reduced instruction set computing|RISC]] processor used in the original [[Acorn Archimedes]] and one of the first RISC processors. However, when the company was incorporated in 1990, the acronym was changed to stand for "Advanced RISC Machines" in the company name "Advanced RISC Machines Ltd." Then, at the time of the [[Initial public offering|IPO]] in 1998, the company name was changed to "ARM Holdings",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://quotes.nasdaq.com/asp/SummaryQuote.asp?symbol=ARMH&selected=ARMH |title=ARM Holdings, plc, Company Description <U+2013> NASDAQ.com |publisher=Quotes.nasdaq.com |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> often just called ARM just as the processors.

===Founding===
The company was founded in November 1990 as '''Advanced RISC Machines Ltd''' and structured as a [[joint venture]] between [[Acorn Computers]], Apple Computer (now [[Apple Inc.]]) and [[VLSI Technology]].<ref>[http://www.arm.com/aboutarm/milestones.html ARM milestones], ARM company website. Retrieved 5 February 2008</ref><ref name='andrews-co-verification-of-hardware-and-software-for-ARM-SoC-design'>{{cite book| last1 = Andrews| first1 = Jason| title = Co-verification of hardware and software for ARM SoC design| chapter = 3 SoC Verification Topics for the ARM Architecture| publisher = [[Elsevier]]| year = 2005| location = Oxford, UK| pages = 69| isbn = 0-7506-7730-9| quote = ARM started as a branch of Acorn Computer in Cambridge, England, with the formation of a joint venture between Acorn, Apple and VLSI Technology. A team of twelve employees produced the design of the first ARM microprocessor between 1983 and 1985.}}</ref><ref name="latimes apple to join acorn">{{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-28/business/fi-4993_1_arm-chips | title=Apple to Join Acorn, VLSI in Chip-Making Venture |work=Los Angeles Times | date=28 November 1990 | accessdate=6 February 2012 | author=Weber, Jonathan | location=Los Angeles | quote=Apple has invested about $3 million (roughly 1.5 million pounds) for a 30% interest in the company, dubbed Advanced Risc Machines Ltd. (ARM) [...]}}</ref> The new company intended to further the development of the [[ARM architecture|Acorn RISC Machine]] processor, which was originally used in the Acorn Archimedes and had been selected by Apple for their [[Apple Newton|Newton]] project. Its first profitable year was 1993. The company's Silicon Valley and Tokyo offices were opened in 1994. In 1997, ARM invested in Palmchip Corporation to provide a system on chip platforms and to enter into the disk drive market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1210443|title=PALMCHIP Introduces Fully-Integrated, Low-Power Controller Core for OEM Mass Storage Design|date=16 May 1997|publisher=[[EE Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arm.com/about/company-profile/milestones.php?fullsite=yes|title=ARM Company Milestones|publisher=ARM Holdings}}</ref> In 1998 the Company changed its name from ''Advanced RISC Machines Ltd'' to ''ARM Ltd''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_/ai_53093087 |title=Advanced RISC Machines Ltd is now ARM Ltd |publisher=Findarticles.com |date=19 October 1998 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The Company was first listed on the London Stock Exchange and [[NASDAQ]] in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0CGN/is_/ai_20505833 |title=ARM wins billion dollar valuation in IPO |publisher=Findarticles.com |date=20 April 1998 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> Apple's shareholding had fallen to 14.8% by February 1999.<ref name="cnet short take">{{cite news | url=http://news.cnet.com/Short-Take-Apple-sells-ARM-shares/2110-1001_3-221149.html | title=Short Take: Apple sells ARM shares | work=CNET | date=3 February 1999 | accessdate=6 February 2012 | author=Davis, Jim | quote=Apple still holds 14.8 percent of ARM [...]}}</ref>

In 2010, ARM joined with [[IBM]], [[Texas Instruments]], [[Samsung]], [[ST-Ericsson]] and [[Freescale Semiconductor]] in forming a [[Nonprofit organization|Not For Profit]] [[Open Source]] engineering company, [[Linaro]].<ref>[http://www.dailytech.com/IBM+Freescale+Samsung+Form+Linaro+to+Aid+in+Developing+ARMcompatible+Software/article18611.htm IBM, Freescale, Samsung Form Linaro to Aid in Developing ARM-compatible Software] Daily Tech, 5 June 2010</ref>

