==Partnerships==

===Microsoft===
At 2011 CES, [[Microsoft]] revealed that Windows 8 operating system will run on ARM architecture platforms.<ref>Tony Bradley, PCWorld. "[http://www.pcworld.com/businesscenter/article/215779/windows_8_on_arm_expands_microsofts_mobile_horizons.html Windows 8 on ARM Expands Microsoft's Mobile Horizons]." 6 January 2011. Retrieved 8 July 2011.</ref> Following this, [[Microsoft]] demonstrated Internet Explorer 10. For around 30 seconds of the 90-minute talk, they mentioned that some of the demos were running on an ARM computer.<ref>Keir Thomas, PCWorld. "[http://www.pcworld.com/businesscenter/article/225217/microsoft_demos_ie10_on_arm_and_it_looks_good.html#tk.mod_rel Microsoft Demos IE10 on ARM, and It Looks Good]." 14 April 2011. Retrieved 8 July 2011.</ref>
During [[Microsoft]]'s presentation of [[Windows 8]] on 1 June 2011, a handful of the company's hardware partners showed off tablets and notebooks running the OS, including ARM instead of Intel or AMD.<ref>Keir Thomas, PCWorld. "[http://www.pcworld.com/article/229241/windows_8_and_the_arm_revolution_the_pros_and_cons.html Windows 8 and the ARM Revolution: The Pros and Cons]." 2 June 2011. Retrieved 8 July 2011.</ref>

===University of Michigan===
In 2011, ARM renewed a five-year, $5 million research partnership with [[University of Michigan]], which extended their existing research partnership to 2015. This partnership will focus on ultra-low energy and [[Green computing|sustainable computing]].<ref>Peter Clarke, EE Times. "[http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4219482/ARM-extends-Michigan-research-deal ARM extends Michigan research deal]." 31 August 2011. Retrieved 20 September 2011.</ref><ref>Chris Edwards, Electronics Weekly. "[http://www.electronicsweekly.com/blogs/low-power-design/2011/08/arm-extends-michigan-low-power-work.html ARM extends Michigan low-power work]." 31 August 2011. Retrieved 20 September 2011.</ref>

==Senior management==
[[Warren East]] was appointed Chief Executive Officer of ARM Holdings in October 2001. In the 2011 financial year, East received a total compensation of <U+00A3>1,187,500 from ARM, comprising a salary of <U+00A3>475,000 and a bonus of <U+00A3>712,500.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Warren East: Executive Profile & Biography |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=1507093&ticker=ARM:LN|work=BusinessWeek |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Warren East profile |url=http://people.forbes.com/profile/warren-east/7332 |work=Forbes |accessdate=23 August 2009}}</ref> East said in March 2013 that he would retire from ARM in May, with president [[Simon Segars]] taking over as CEO.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARM CEO Warren East steps down |url=http://www.pcpro.co.uk/news/380650/arm-ceo-warren-east-steps-down |publisher=PC Pro|accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref> In March 2014, former Rexam chairman Stuart Chambers succeeded John Buchanan as chairman. Chambers, a non-executive director of Tesco and former chief executive of Nippon Sheet Glass Group, had previously worked at Mars and Royal Dutch Shell.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Appointment Of New Chairman |url=http://ir.arm.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=197211&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1893629&highlight=
|work=ARM Investor Relations |publisher=ARM Investor Relations |accessdate=12 March 2014}}</ref>

